---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";

const title = "Hong Kong Salaries Tax Guide 2024/25: Rates, Allowances & Calculator";
const description = "Complete Hong Kong salaries tax guide for 2024/25. Learn progressive rates, standard rate, personal allowances, MPF deductions, and how to use our Hong Kong tax calculator.";
const image = "/images/blogs/hong-kong-salaries-tax-guide.svg";
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} image={image}>
  <div class="min-h-screen bg-canvas dark:bg-primary">
    <main class="min-h-screen">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="mb-6 text-sm">
          <ol class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2">
            <li class="flex items-center gap-2"><a href="/" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Home</a></li>
            <li class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-muted">/</span><a href="/blogs" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Blogs</a></li>
            <li class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-muted">/</span><span class="font-medium text-ink dark:text-on-primary" aria-current="page">Hong Kong Salaries Tax Guide</span></li>
          </ol>
        </nav>

        <article class="prose max-w-none">
          <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-ink mb-4 dark:text-on-primary">Hong Kong Salaries Tax Guide 2024/25: Rates, Allowances & Calculator</h1>
          <p class="text-lg text-body dark:text-muted">Last updated: July 2026 | 11 min read</p>

          <div class="mt-8 space-y-6 text-body dark:text-muted">
            <p>Hong Kong salaries tax is one of the lowest-income tax regimes in the world, making it a major draw for professionals and expatriates. For the 2024/25 year of assessment, salaries tax applies to income from employment at rates that start at 2% and rise to a maximum of 17%. This guide covers the 2024/25 salaries tax structure, personal allowances, MPF deductions, filing requirements, and common pitfalls taxpayers face.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Overview of Hong Kong Salaries Tax</h2>
            <p>Salaries tax is levied on individuals who derive income from employment in Hong Kong. The Inland Revenue Department (IRD) administers salaries tax under the Inland Revenue Ordinance. Key features include a territorial basis of assessment, generous personal allowances, and the option to choose between the progressive rate system and the standard rate to minimize tax liability. The 2024/25 year of assessment covers income earned from April 1, 2024, to March 31, 2025.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Progressive Rates System</h2>
            <p>Under the progressive rates system, salaries tax is calculated using a series of net chargeable income brackets. Tax is applied at rates starting from 2% and increasing to 17% on higher brackets. The net chargeable income is computed by deducting approved charitable donations and allowable deductions from the total assessable income. The progressive system is designed to be progressive, meaning lower-income taxpayers pay a smaller percentage of their income in tax.</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
              <li>The first HK$50,000 of net chargeable income is taxed at 2%</li>
              <li>The next HK$50,000 is taxed at 6%</li>
              <li>The next HK$40,000 is taxed at 10%</li>
              <li>The next HK$40,000 is taxed at 14%</li>
              <li>Remaining net chargeable income is taxed at 17%</li>
            </ul>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Standard Rate System</h2>
            <p>The standard rate is an alternative method of charging salaries tax. It is calculated by applying a flat rate to your total assessable income after deducting allowable outgoings and MPF contributions, but before deducting personal allowances. Many taxpayers find the standard rate produces a lower tax bill, especially those with high incomes relative to their allowances. You cannot claim personal allowances under the standard rate, so it is essential to compare both methods when filing your tax return.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Personal Allowances for 2024/25</h2>
            <p>The IRD provides several personal allowances to reduce your net chargeable income. For the 2024/25 year of assessment, the basic allowance is HK$132,000 per person. Married persons may claim a married person allowance of HK$264,000 if they file jointly or if one spouse elects to be assessed separately. Additional allowances include child allowances, dependent parent allowances, and dependent grandparent allowances, which provide further relief for families with dependents. These allowances are automatically applied if you have no income, but if you earn income, you can only claim them against the first year they arise or when your spouse's income falls below a certain threshold.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">MPF Deductions and Tax Benefits</h2>
            <p>Mandatory Provident Fund (MPF) contributions are deductible from your assessable income for salaries tax purposes. Both employee and employer mandatory contributions are deductible, subject to a maximum of HK$18,000 per year for each of the top-up and mandatory portions. Voluntary contributions up to certain limits may also qualify for tax deductions. MPF deductions are particularly valuable because they reduce your assessable income directly, potentially lowering your tax under both the progressive rate and standard rate calculations. Use our <a href="/countries/hong-kong/salaries-tax/salaries-tax-calculator" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Hong Kong salaries tax calculator</a> to model different contribution scenarios and see how they impact your tax bill.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Who Needs to File Salaries Tax</h2>
            <p>You are liable for salaries tax if you derive income from employment sourced in Hong Kong, regardless of where you reside. The source of employment is determined by the place where the employment contract was negotiated, signed, and performed. Employment income is sourced in Hong Kong if your employment contract is entered into in Hong Kong and your employer is a Hong Kong resident, even if you work outside Hong Kong under that contract. The IRD provides detailed guidance on source rules, and cross-border employees may have dual-source or foreign-source income that requires careful assessment.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">How to File Your Salaries Tax Return</h2>
            <p>The IRD issues individual tax returns around May each year for the preceding year. You must complete and return the form within one month of the issue date. If you receive more than one tax form, you should complete the one that applies to your circumstances. For taxpayers with straightforward returns, self-assessment is available. You can also file online through the eTAX system, which provides faster processing and the ability to view your assessment and pay tax electronically. Our <a href="/blogs/hong-kong-etax-guide" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">eTAX guide</a> covers the online filing process step by step.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
              <li>Failing to declare foreign-source employment income when you have a Hong Kong employment contract</li>
              <li>Overlooking MPF contributions and allowable deductions that reduce tax</li>
              <li>Missing the tax return filing deadline and incurring late-filing penalties</li>
              <li>Not claiming the correct personal allowances, such as the married person allowance when eligible</li>
              <li>Confusing salaries tax with property tax or profits tax on business income</li>
            </ul>
            <p>By understanding these common errors and using our <a href="/countries/hong-kong/salaries-tax/salaries-tax-calculator" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Hong Kong salaries tax calculator</a>, you can ensure accurate filings and minimize your tax liability. For further details on allowable deductions, read our <a href="/blogs/hong-kong-tax-allowances-deductions" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Hong Kong tax allowances and deductions guide</a>.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">What is the salaries tax rate in Hong Kong for 2024/25?</h3>
            <p>The progressive salaries tax rate ranges from 2% to 17% for 2024/25. The exact rate depends on your net chargeable income after allowances and deductions. You can compare it against the standard rate to determine which method produces a lower tax.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Can I claim MPF deductions for salaries tax?</h3>
            <p>Yes, mandatory MPF contributions are deductible from assessable income. Both employee and employer mandatory contributions are deductible up to the annual maximum of HK$18,000 each.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Who is considered a Hong Kong tax resident?</h3>
            <p>A Hong Kong tax resident is typically someone who ordinarily resides in Hong Kong or who stays in Hong Kong for more than 180 days in the year of assessment. Tax residents are taxed on Hong Kong-sourced employment income. For a detailed analysis, see our <a href="/blogs/hong-kong-tax-residency" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Hong Kong tax residency guide</a>.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">What happens if I file my salaries tax return late?</h3>
            <p>Late filing may result in a penalty of up to HK$10,000. The IRD may also issue a surcharge of up to 5% of the tax due if payment is also late. To avoid penalties, file within the one-month deadline and pay provisional tax on time.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Do I need to pay provisional salaries tax?</h3>
            <p>Yes, if your total tax payable exceeds a certain threshold, the IRD will require you to pay provisional tax in two installments for the following year. For more information, see our <a href="/blogs/hong-kong-provisional-tax-guide" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Hong Kong provisional tax guide</a>.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">How do I find my tax records online?</h3>
            <p>You can use the eTAX system to view your assessment notices, pay tax, and apply for a holdover. See our <a href="/blogs/hong-kong-etax-guide" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Hong Kong eTAX guide</a> for instructions.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Is overseas income taxable in Hong Kong?</h3>
            <p>Overseas income is generally not taxable unless it is derived from a Hong Kong business or employment. However, if your employment contract is executed in Hong Kong, employment income from working outside Hong Kong may still be taxable on a Hong Kong source basis. The IRD's 60-day rule applies to certain short-term employment.</p>
          </div>

